  "Evidence for the shift of the pronunciation of these letters": [
   {
    "text": "Some linguists posit that the reason shorushim ending in gutterals have an \"extra\" vowel sound (",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "type": "italics",
    "tokens": [
     {
      "text": "po-say-ach",
      "type": "text"
     }
    ]
   },
   {
    "text": " as opposed to, e.g. ",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "type": "italics",
    "tokens": [
     {
      "text": "kos-eiv",
      "type": "text"
     }
    ]
   },
   {
    "text": ") is because the real sound for a ח or ע is so low in the throat that the jaw needs to open fully to pronounce them, causing the shift from \"ei\" to \"ah,\" unlike the similar כ or א letters which are just pronounced at the back of the mouth, without opening the throat, and can therefore accomidate an \"ei\" vowel.",
    "type": "text"
   }
  ],
